WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.840
Hi, my name is Andrew Batran, and I'm a data reporter for the Washington Post's investigative

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:10.840
team.

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:16.299
And I'm here to talk about The Opioid Files and how we investigated pharmaceutical companies

00:00:16.299 --> 00:00:19.480
and the government and made data accessible to all.

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:25.799
This is a two-week-year-old boy in an isolation ward in West Virginia.

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:31.340
Any sound seriously disturbs him and he won't stop crying, and that's because he was born

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:33.560
addicted to opioids.

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:38.099
And he is one among thousands of children separated from their parents and families

00:00:38.099 --> 00:00:43.660
and forced into state care by an opioid epidemic that has fractured families in every corner

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:44.660
of the country.

00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:52.740
In West Virginia alone, more than 5,200 lives over the past few decades have been lost.

00:00:52.740 --> 00:00:55.139
And we've seen the effects of this.

00:00:55.139 --> 00:00:59.419
We know that the number of children in foster care in West Virginia has doubled ever since

00:00:59.419 --> 00:01:02.700
the epidemic started.

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:07.620
And other effects that we've been able to see are the death rates in communities across

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:08.860
the country.

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:16.459
In West Virginia, we can see the effects of the opioid death rates, and we can also see

00:01:16.459 --> 00:01:22.339
that there were also higher rates of child abuse and neglect claims in those same areas.

00:01:22.339 --> 00:01:26.099
State officials said that more than 80% of children in foster care have been affected

00:01:26.099 --> 00:01:29.139
by the drug epidemic.

00:01:29.139 --> 00:01:34.699
So we've seen the effects, but we've never really been able to see the causes before,

00:01:34.699 --> 00:01:36.699
not with a lot of specificity.

00:01:36.699 --> 00:01:43.099
But the thing is, pharmaceutical companies and the Drug Enforcement Administration have

00:01:43.099 --> 00:01:48.900
been able to see this for the longest time, because every single pill from manufacturer

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:59.300
to distributor to pharmacy is tracked in a data set, and is called the Automated Reports

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:04.260
and Consolidated Ords System.

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:08.300
And the Drug Enforcement Administration is also under the Department of Justice.

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:15.220
And it's tracked because prescription pain pills are scheduled to drug, which means it

00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:20.020
has a high potential for abuse, with use potentially leading to severe psychological

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:22.940
and physical dependence.

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:28.339
And we call it ARCOS for short.

00:02:28.339 --> 00:02:33.139
And so pharmaceutical companies and the government have known the scope of this data for the

00:02:33.139 --> 00:02:38.259
longest time, the reach of the spread of these pills.

00:02:38.259 --> 00:02:40.820
And journalists and researchers have tried to get this data set for the longest time

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:41.820
as well.

00:02:42.539 --> 00:02:46.539
But we've only been able to get it at the aggregate level, maybe by state, maybe by

00:02:46.539 --> 00:02:51.419
county, maybe by zip code, maybe by overall drug.

00:02:51.419 --> 00:02:55.059
We've never been able to get it at the raw data set level, where we could really dig

00:02:55.059 --> 00:02:57.339
into the nuances of the data.

00:02:57.339 --> 00:03:02.580
Every time we've made a request for it, it's been denied.

00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:08.860
That is until recently.

00:03:08.860 --> 00:03:12.300
So for context, the most powerful people in the pharmaceutical America didn't want

00:03:12.300 --> 00:03:13.300
it released.

00:03:13.300 --> 00:03:16.339
And a lot of the most powerful people in the Department of Justice didn't want this data

00:03:16.339 --> 00:03:17.339
released.

00:03:17.339 --> 00:03:23.339
However, when 2,000 communities across the US sued dozens of big drug companies over

00:03:23.339 --> 00:03:29.979
the destruction that painkillers were causing across the country, a federal judge ordered

00:03:29.979 --> 00:03:35.419
that the ARCOS data set be made available to those plaintiffs for examination.

00:03:35.419 --> 00:03:41.020
However, they sealed it away from the public and from the media.

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:46.259
And so the Washington Post, as well as the Charleston Gazette-Mail sued for access to

00:03:46.259 --> 00:03:48.979
that data.

00:03:48.979 --> 00:03:51.860
And so we appealed the decision.

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:55.380
And a group of appellate judges ruled that the protective order on the ARCOS data should

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:56.380
be amended.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:04:06.179
In effect, they released data from 2006 to 2012, and eventually 2014.

00:04:06.179 --> 00:04:10.220
And so we got our hands on the data the day it was released.

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:14.460
And what we found out was that the data set was huge.

00:04:14.460 --> 00:04:19.260
It had about 42 columns, which isn't too bad, but it had literally hundreds of millions

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:26.660
of rows of data for every pain pill order sold between 2006 and eventually 2014.

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:30.739
And so the team of us, there were about three data reporters, including myself.

00:04:30.739 --> 00:04:36.899
We used a mix of different statistical analyzing languages, like Python and R.

00:04:36.899 --> 00:04:42.179
And so in order to maintain great communication between the two, we used data structures that

00:04:42.179 --> 00:04:46.459
could operate between the two languages, such as Parquet and Feather.

00:04:46.459 --> 00:04:53.459
And because the data sets were so huge, we used packages like doParallel in order to

00:04:53.459 --> 00:04:57.700
handle all that.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:06.980
And in order to exchange our analysis methodologies and reports, we wrote up everything in Jupyter

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:09.500
Notebooks or R Markdown.

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:16.260
I also created a Shiny app so that we could investigate and dig into pharmacies that looked

00:05:17.059 --> 00:05:22.459
suspicious, because any way you might have sliced it would raise a different set of pharmacies

00:05:22.459 --> 00:05:28.500
that might have set off some suspicious orders.

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:34.339
And so this data set was revelatory because it showed where each pill moved from manufacturer

00:05:34.339 --> 00:05:37.899
to distributor to pharmacy for the first time.

00:05:37.899 --> 00:05:40.540
And so we could see everything both in aggregate and fine detail.

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:43.980
And this is what we found out.

00:05:43.980 --> 00:05:51.619
We could see that 100 billion pills saturated the country between 2006 and 2014.

00:05:51.619 --> 00:05:56.299
And pharmaceutical companies from manufacturers to distributors to pharmacies made billions

00:05:56.299 --> 00:05:59.299
of dollars a year.

00:05:59.299 --> 00:06:03.660
We could finally see the connection between the deaths from opioids and how they soared

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:06.059
in communities that were flooded with pain pills.

00:06:06.059 --> 00:06:11.220
And we saw that the highest per capita death rates nationwide were in rural West Virginia,

00:06:11.220 --> 00:06:14.500
Kentucky, and Virginia.

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:22.260
And we could see that just six companies distributed 76% of the pills during this period.

00:06:22.260 --> 00:06:27.859
And we could drill down into individual drug companies and pharmacy companies like Walgreens,

00:06:27.859 --> 00:06:32.299
where we noticed that at the height of the crisis, Walgreens sold about nearly one out

00:06:32.299 --> 00:06:38.660
of five of the most addictive opioids, and that they had a really, really interesting

00:06:38.660 --> 00:06:40.779
company structure.

00:06:40.779 --> 00:06:49.540
They not only had a franchise of pharmacies out there, they also owned a distribution

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:51.299
company as well.

00:06:51.299 --> 00:06:54.279
So it was very much vertical integration all the way.

00:06:54.279 --> 00:07:00.140
So while a lot of mom and pop pharmacies could argue that they didn't really know exactly

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:07.260
the impact of all the surge in orders for opioids in their pharmacy, Walgreens knew

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:13.339
exactly how much and where these pills were going.

00:07:13.339 --> 00:07:19.980
And so we went through the effort of geocoding 200,000 or so pharmacies so that we could

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:26.980
put it on a map and then really analyze geographic patterns that way.

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:33.299
And we made an interactive that allowed people to search their local pharmacy and see the

00:07:33.299 --> 00:07:39.500
scale of sales they did compared to their neighbors.

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:45.619
And so we could really drill down in individual pharmacies like this one in Florida.

00:07:45.619 --> 00:07:49.339
This is a Walgreens in Florida.

00:07:49.339 --> 00:07:54.700
And what's important to really note is that it was the law for these companies to implement

00:07:54.700 --> 00:08:00.179
in an effective system for monitoring their opioid sales for suspicious orders.

00:08:00.179 --> 00:08:05.980
And so we found so many pharmacies that violated those suspicious orders but kept selling

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:06.980
anyway.

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:13.420
This is an example of a store in Oviedo, Florida, where starting in 2011, sales started spiking.

00:08:13.420 --> 00:08:18.980
You can see it's declined a little bit after legislators passed a bill to limit the sales

00:08:18.980 --> 00:08:26.619
for a specific type of oxycodone, which slowed it for a month until customers realized they

00:08:26.619 --> 00:08:31.540
could order a different type of milligram strength and get that much easier.

00:08:31.540 --> 00:08:35.619
And so that started spiking even more exponentially.

00:08:35.619 --> 00:08:41.380
It got so bad that a police chief in that town made so many arrests that he wrote a

00:08:41.380 --> 00:08:47.580
message to Walgreens executives begging them to change their policies and to restrict it

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:53.219
more and to not sell to people who had been previously arrested for selling opioids on

00:08:53.219 --> 00:08:59.219
the street and to stop selling to people who had been rejected from other pharmacies

00:08:59.219 --> 00:09:02.659
with the same prescription.

00:09:02.659 --> 00:09:06.820
But you can see it stopped for maybe a month or slowed down for about a month until it

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:10.820
started growing in sales once again.

00:09:10.820 --> 00:09:17.880
And it wasn't until around 2012 that sales finally stopped slowing, started slowing down.

00:09:17.880 --> 00:09:22.900
But that was when they started realizing that the DEA was investigating several stores as

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:29.940
well as distribution center until eventually that store was suspended.

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:38.539
And then the distribution center itself in Florida that also got suspended.

00:09:38.539 --> 00:09:45.739
You can see here that it sent billions of pills a month to Walgreens stores across the

00:09:45.739 --> 00:09:47.820
Southeast and Florida.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:54.380
And you can see here, thanks to the data, that even though they had been halted starting

00:09:54.380 --> 00:09:59.219
in 2012, that another distribution center stepped up to fill those orders that this

00:09:59.219 --> 00:10:03.260
particular distribution center stopped handling.

00:10:03.260 --> 00:10:10.099
So Walgreens barely slowed down their sales.

00:10:10.099 --> 00:10:13.380
What was interesting about this data set and the story that we did was that we made the

00:10:13.380 --> 00:10:16.739
data widely available to the public.

00:10:16.739 --> 00:10:21.419
And we put out explicit instructions on how to use the data as well.

00:10:21.419 --> 00:10:27.380
Because the thing is, the data set was so huge that there were more stories that we

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:31.179
could possibly tell by ourselves.

00:10:31.179 --> 00:10:38.340
And the data could be applied to specific communities to see what they thought was more

00:10:38.340 --> 00:10:42.700
interesting and applied to them.

00:10:42.859 --> 00:10:48.700
So in the first main page where you could see the results of the opioid sales across

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:53.580
the country, there was a section where folks could navigate and find their state and their

00:10:53.580 --> 00:10:57.900
county and see exactly how many pills were sold there, which were the top distributors,

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:03.500
which were the top manufacturers, which were the top pharmacies, and get the numbers for

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:04.500
them.

00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:10.940
And not only that, get generated viz specific to their county, and also the summarized tables,

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:14.619
as well as the raw data itself, if they wanted to do more deeper analysis.

00:11:14.619 --> 00:11:23.099
On top of that, we took that data and we used Plummer to create an API out of it.

00:11:23.099 --> 00:11:30.700
And what was great about Plummer is that with very little coding, it will self-generate

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:35.260
some great documentation behind this data portal.

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:43.299
We also created an R wrapper around it for more ease for the special R users.

00:11:43.299 --> 00:11:49.500
And then a researcher out of Maryland saw this and reached out and went and made a Python

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:53.460
package around this as well.

00:11:53.460 --> 00:12:00.219
And on top of that, we created a bunch of vignettes and walkthroughs so that folks could

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:05.219
see exactly how we did our work, but also figure out how to tell stories relevant to

00:12:05.219 --> 00:12:06.859
their communities as well.

00:12:06.859 --> 00:12:13.219
And we included functionality in the package to slice out the data beyond what we had done

00:12:13.219 --> 00:12:22.500
in our stories ourselves, such as being able to look at individual drugs in the data set.

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:28.179
For our stories, we focused on oxycodone and hydrocodone, but there are 12 other drugs

00:12:28.179 --> 00:12:32.539
in this data set from Arcos that we didn't even look at.

00:12:32.539 --> 00:12:39.460
The map on the right visualizes all the methadone sales in Boston.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:44.219
It's this area called Methadone Mile.

00:12:44.219 --> 00:12:50.500
And we made sure a bunch of functions, include a bunch of functions that we anticipated people

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:54.500
would find useful, such as bringing in the lab to log it in for all the pharmacies that

00:12:54.500 --> 00:12:56.059
we looked up.

00:12:56.059 --> 00:13:01.460
We brought in population tables for state, county, and all the years the data was available

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:04.020
so that folks could normalize it well.

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:12.059
And also all the summarized tables, because it was important to make data accessible.

00:13:12.059 --> 00:13:17.059
It wasn't just enough to put a data set on GitHub or put a link out there and then let

00:13:17.059 --> 00:13:23.219
people go through it themselves and figure out how to do it, deal with it, which researchers

00:13:23.219 --> 00:13:24.619
are great at doing.

00:13:25.179 --> 00:13:30.340
They can create so many great research projects around it, such as the effects of the opioid

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:33.700
epidemic on the housing market, for example.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:40.140
But we went through the effort of allowing many doorways to this data, through the API,

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:47.419
through the browser itself on that main page, so that anyone with any level of, with different

00:13:47.419 --> 00:13:52.619
levels of expertise could access this data.

00:13:52.619 --> 00:14:01.260
And sometimes it can convert others to R, which I find is a success.

00:14:01.260 --> 00:14:09.539
So after we put all that data out there, we found out that within a few days, hundreds

00:14:09.539 --> 00:14:16.299
of stories were written by local journalists, and it was amazing.

00:14:16.299 --> 00:14:21.700
For example, the Cleveland Plains dealer looked at the data and found that there was one particular

00:14:21.780 --> 00:14:26.780
small-town doctor that was responsible for selling 1.6 million pills, which helped fuel

00:14:26.780 --> 00:14:29.659
the surge there in Ohio.

00:14:29.659 --> 00:14:36.219
A radio station, WOSU, looked at the data and decided to focus on the victims and telling

00:14:36.219 --> 00:14:40.500
their stories as well as the stories of those who were left behind.

00:14:40.500 --> 00:14:47.340
The Daily Union in Wisconsin looked at the data and tracked down the businesses who were

00:14:47.340 --> 00:14:52.820
selling the most pills, and then went to see how much they had donated to politicians

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:55.539
and to whom.

00:14:55.539 --> 00:15:01.260
The Philadelphia Inquirer made some great interactive visualizations that showed how

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:06.859
after OxyContin was reformulated so that it was not as crushable and snortable, that the

00:15:06.859 --> 00:15:13.260
demand for a different type of Oxycodone surged instead.

00:15:13.260 --> 00:15:18.700
And through the data, we were able to look at manufacturers in a new way.

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:24.859
So while Purdue got all the attention based on the data, we could see that they only controlled

00:15:24.859 --> 00:15:32.780
about 3% of the opioid market, and that three lesser-known generic drug manufacturers actually

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:35.619
manufactured most of the addictive pills.

00:15:36.500 --> 00:15:44.260
However, since they weren't well-known, they avoided DEA scrutiny for many years.

00:15:44.260 --> 00:15:50.260
Journalists also saw through the data that lawmakers were involved in this.

00:15:50.260 --> 00:15:56.460
One lawmaker in Louisiana, a House member, owned two pharmacies that were 12.5 miles

00:15:56.460 --> 00:16:04.500
apart from each other in a town that served 6,000 people, but sold 1.5 million pills in

00:16:04.500 --> 00:16:07.380
that time period.

00:16:07.380 --> 00:16:11.900
Another legislator that journalists found in the data set was a state representative

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:21.619
in Tennessee who was president and CEO of the largest orderers of opioids in the state.

00:16:21.619 --> 00:16:27.380
And what journalists connected with that was that earlier in the year, this particular

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:34.780
state lawmaker, Shane Reeves, actually introduced and helped pass a law that made it easier

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:40.299
to access opioid prescriptions.

00:16:40.299 --> 00:16:44.539
And so as a result of all this, four companies that made or distributed prescription opioids

00:16:44.539 --> 00:16:49.539
and played roles in the catastrophic opioid crisis have reached a tentative $26 billion

00:16:49.539 --> 00:16:54.340
settlement with counties and cities that sued them for damages in the largest federal court

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:58.020
case in American history.

00:16:58.020 --> 00:17:02.020
And internal documents out of all this showed that the pressure within the drug companies

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:10.540
to sell opioids were in conflict with numerous red flags from the DEA and even internal workers.

00:17:10.540 --> 00:17:16.660
But the profits are so huge that sales didn't slow down.

00:17:16.660 --> 00:17:23.739
And we're still feeling the effects to this day in a different way.

00:17:23.739 --> 00:17:28.579
Prescription pain pills were the main cause of overdose deaths through 2011.

00:17:28.579 --> 00:17:33.540
But then after laws were passed, after pharmacists caught on, after doctors caught on and started

00:17:33.540 --> 00:17:40.020
restricting access to prescription pain pills, drug users then turned to heroin, which set

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:42.500
the stage for fentanyl.

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:47.339
And together, oxycodone, hydrocodone, heroin, and fentanyl have killed more than 400,000

00:17:47.339 --> 00:17:51.660
Americans since the turn of the century, a quarter of whom have died from fentanyl in

00:17:51.660 --> 00:17:57.140
just the last six years.

00:17:57.140 --> 00:18:03.380
So I'm not exactly sure how to wrap up this talk, but I want to point out that I hope

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:13.739
the data that should have been kept an eye on by pharmaceutical companies, by the government,

00:18:13.739 --> 00:18:17.540
and has finally made it into the hands of the public, to the researchers and journalists

00:18:17.540 --> 00:18:25.260
out there, I hope we're able to hold everyone more accountable so that we can prevent more

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:27.380
foster care children.

00:18:27.380 --> 00:18:32.380
Anyway, that's my talk.

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:33.099
Thanks so much for listening.

